courses.learning_outcomes:
After taking this course, students will be able to:

1. explain how cultures function, and recognize the different perspectives that can be used to understand culture;
2. discuss how different cultures have both diverse and similar solutions to the problems of human existence;
3. analyze cultures and societies as informed through comparisons with other cultures and societies; and
4. explicate the connections among different subfields of social and cultural anthropology (which focus on different facets of culture, such as religion, gender, politics, economics, etc.) and how these facets are linked and integrated in each culture

By the end of this course, students will

1) understand how anthropology is practiced in its different areas and fields;
2) know the basics of how to write papers and how to most fruitfully proceed in their studies as anthropology students in the university;
3) know the department's different teachers and the different ways in which they envision anthropology; and

4) have a broad overall sense of what anthropology as a discipline consists of.

1) To learn field research techniques for ethnographic study;
2) To develop skills and knowledge in designing and carrying our research projects independently;
3) To enhance effective communication and writing abilities;
4) To be aware of ethical and personal issues of field research.

Upon completing this course, students will be able to:

1. analyze the globalization of culture, a process taking place across the world today and shaping all of our lives;
2. recognize different aspects of the globalization of culture, including those involving recent history, economics, consumption, mass media, migration, and cultural identity;
3. discuss the costs and benefits of contemporary processes of globalization to individuals, societies, and the world; and
4. evaluate the nature of your own culture and selves within a globalizing world.

Students taking this course will:

1) learn to see the cultural nature of the economy and of power;
2) be able to understand how economic behavior that seems irrational in market capitalist contexts can make sense in other cultural contexts;
3) learn how to combine universalizing theories and ethnographic understanding of particular cultures;
4) understand the way the culture of capitalism shapes the way we see the world and affects our behavior;
5) be aware of the history of ecological degradation, consumerism, globalization, nationalism, and fundamentalist religions, and see how they are related to each other.

Upon completing this course, students will:
- -have a general understanding of the subdisciplines of anthropology;
- -know the key concepts of the field;
- -know the major theories that explain human cultural and societal diversity and complexity;
- -be able to use the discipline’s holistic approach to understand human societies and cultures.

Students will
1. understand how culture shapes societies’ understandings of the body, love and emotions;
2. comprehend how culturual, social, political, historical, and commercial aspects of body, love and emotions are lined and interrelated;
3. be able to use ethnographic approaches to study of the body and emotions, in particular the value of participant-observation fieldwork methodologies;
4. understand how the study of the body, love, and emotions contributes to central anthropological concepts, frameworks, debates and theories;
5. be able to discuss significant issues concerning corporeal and emotional life in their own culture so that they can better comprehend how local identities are formed and contested in a globalizing world.

